{"text": " I have a question, what's the biggest planet we've ever found? Not in our solar system. I know Jupiter is the biggest here, by a lot. You could fit 11 Earths along Jupiter's diameter. Now, I mean, in the whole observable universe, our first contender is huge. It's got the biggest radius measured with high confidence, 2.08 times bigger than Jupiter, meaning you could fit 23 Earths across it. This planet's awesome. It's less dense than marshmallows. But if you're good with a little more scientific uncertainty, because we haven't been able to measure this one in the most accurate ways, our second contender looks like it's even bigger. 2.5 times the radius of Jupiter, you could line up 27.5 Earths inside it. And this planet is so far from its star that one of its years is equal to 1,968 Earth years. And finally, the Whopper. If you're okay with even more scientific uncertainty, because scientists think this one's got a swirling envelope of gas and dust around it. But it looks like its radius could be up to 6.9 times bigger than Jupiter's, meaning 76 Earths. If true, that would make this the biggest planet we've ever found. And this one's a proto planet, still forming, so we're watching to see what it becomes. And if you think there should be more optimistic science and tech stories, follow us.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 3.7600000000000002, "text": " I have a question, what's the biggest planet we've ever found?", "tokens": [50364, 286, 362, 257, 1168, 11, 437, 311, 264, 3880, 5054, 321, 600, 1562, 1352, 30, 50552], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16107191041458485, "compression_ratio": 1.628158844765343, "no_speech_prob": 0.0055060600861907005}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 3.7600000000000002, "end": 4.88, "text": " Not in our solar system.", "tokens": [50552, 1726, 294, 527, 7936, 1185, 13, 50608], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16107191041458485, "compression_ratio": 1.628158844765343, "no_speech_prob": 0.00550606